Note:
Runa Standard Library: DataFrame Module

This module implements a comprehensive DataFrame data structure for data science operations,
providing high-performance columnar data manipulation, statistical operations, and seamless
integration with other data science tools. Built for production-grade data processing
with memory-efficient operations and comprehensive type safety.

Key Features:
- High-performance columnar data storage with optimized memory layout
- Comprehensive indexing and selection operations (loc, iloc, boolean indexing)
- Statistical operations (mean, median, std, var, correlation, covariance)
- Data cleaning and transformation (dropna, fillna, pivot, melt, groupby)
- I/O operations with CSV, JSON, and database integration
- Memory-efficient operations with lazy evaluation for large datasets
- Type inference and validation with comprehensive error handling
- Advanced operations (joins, merges, concatenation, reshaping)

Architecture:
Built on Runa's natural language primitives with optimized algorithms for data manipulation.
Provides both pandas-compatible API and native Runa idioms for maximum flexibility
in data science workflows.
:End Note

Import "collections/dict" as dict_utils
Import "collections/list" as list_utils
Import "text/text" as text_utils
Import "math/core" as math_core
Import "csv/csv" as csv_core

Note: DataFrame Core Types and Structure

Type called "DataFrameColumn":
    name as String
    dtype as String
    data as List[Any]
    nullable as Boolean
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "DataFrameIndex":
    labels as List[Any]
    dtype as String
    name as Optional[String]
    is_unique as Boolean
    is_monotonic as Boolean

Type called "DataFrame":
    columns as List[DataFrameColumn]
    index as DataFrameIndex
    shape as List[Integer]
    dtypes as Dictionary[String, String]
    memory_usage as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type DataFrameSelection is Union with:
    | RowSelection with rows as List[Integer]
    | ColumnSelection with columns as List[String]
    | BooleanSelection with mask as List[Boolean]
    | LocationSelection with row_indexer as Any and column_indexer as Any

Type DataFrameResult is Union with:
    | DataFrameSuccess with data as Any
    | DataFrameError with error as DataFrameErrorType

Type DataFrameErrorType is Union with:
    | IndexError with message as String and index as Any
    | ValueError with message as String and value as Any
    | TypeError with message as String and expected_type as String
    | KeyError with message as String and key as String
    | MemoryError with message as String and size_requested as Integer

Note: DataFrame Construction and Factory Functions

Process called "create_dataframe" that takes data as Any and columns as Optional[List[String]] and index as Optional[List[Any]] returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Create DataFrame from various data sources with comprehensive type handling
    Try:
        Match data:
            When Dictionary:
                Return create_dataframe_from_dict with dict_data as data and columns as columns and index as index
            
            When List:
                Return create_dataframe_from_list with list_data as data and columns as columns and index as index
            
            Otherwise:
                Return DataFrameError with error as TypeError with:
                    message as "Unsupported data type for DataFrame construction"
                    expected_type as "Dictionary or List"
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "DataFrame construction failed: " plus error as String
            value as data

Process called "create_dataframe_from_dict" that takes dict_data as Dictionary[String, List[Any]] and columns as Optional[List[String]] and index as Optional[List[Any]] returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Create DataFrame from dictionary with column-oriented data
    Try:
        Let column_names be get_dict_keys with dict as dict_data
        Let num_columns be length of column_names
        
        If num_columns is equal to 0:
            Return create_empty_dataframe with columns as columns and index as index
        
        Note: Validate data consistency and determine shape
        Let first_column_name be column_names at index 0
        Let first_column_data be dict_data at key first_column_name as List[Any]
        Let num_rows be length of first_column_data
        
        Note: Validate all columns have same length
        For each column_name in column_names:
            Let column_data be dict_data at key column_name as List[Any]
            If length of column_data is not equal to num_rows:
                Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
                    message as "All columns must have same length. Column '" plus column_name plus "' has length " plus (length of column_data as String) plus ", expected " plus (num_rows as String)
                    value as column_data
        
        Note: Create columns with type inference
        Let dataframe_columns be empty list
        For each column_name in column_names:
            Let column_data be dict_data at key column_name as List[Any]
            Let inferred_dtype be infer_column_dtype with data as column_data
            
            Let column be DataFrameColumn with:
                name as column_name
                dtype as inferred_dtype
                data as column_data
                nullable as check_column_nullable with data as column_data
                metadata as Dictionary with "source" as "dict_construction"
            
            Add column to dataframe_columns
        
        Note: Create index
        Let dataframe_index be create_dataframe_index with length as num_rows and custom_index as index
        
        Note: Calculate shape and metadata
        Let shape be list containing num_rows, num_columns
        Let dtypes_dict be create_dtypes_dict with columns as dataframe_columns
        Let memory_usage be calculate_memory_usage with columns as dataframe_columns
        
        Let dataframe be DataFrame with:
            columns as dataframe_columns
            index as dataframe_index
            shape as shape
            dtypes as dtypes_dict
            memory_usage as memory_usage
            metadata as Dictionary with:
                "creation_method" as "from_dict"
                "created_at" as get_current_timestamp
        
        Return DataFrameSuccess with data as dataframe
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "Failed to create DataFrame from dictionary: " plus error as String
            value as dict_data

Process called "create_dataframe_from_list" that takes list_data as List[List[Any]] and columns as Optional[List[String]] and index as Optional[List[Any]] returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Create DataFrame from list of rows (row-oriented data)
    Try:
        Let num_rows be length of list_data
        
        If num_rows is equal to 0:
            Return create_empty_dataframe with columns as columns and index as index
        
        Note: Determine number of columns from first row
        Let first_row be list_data at index 0
        Let num_columns be length of first_row
        
        Note: Validate all rows have same length
        For i from 0 to (num_rows minus 1):
            Let row be list_data at index i
            If length of row is not equal to num_columns:
                Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
                    message as "All rows must have same length. Row " plus (i as String) plus " has length " plus (length of row as String) plus ", expected " plus (num_columns as String)
                    value as row
        
        Note: Transpose data to column-oriented format
        Let column_data be empty list
        For col_idx from 0 to (num_columns minus 1):
            Let column_values be empty list
            For row_idx from 0 to (num_rows minus 1):
                Let row be list_data at index row_idx
                Let value be row at index col_idx
                Add value to column_values
            Add column_values to column_data
        
        Note: Generate column names if not provided
        Let column_names be generate_column_names with num_columns as num_columns and custom_columns as columns
        
        Note: Create columns with type inference
        Let dataframe_columns be empty list
        For i from 0 to (num_columns minus 1):
            Let column_name be column_names at index i
            Let column_values be column_data at index i
            Let inferred_dtype be infer_column_dtype with data as column_values
            
            Let column be DataFrameColumn with:
                name as column_name
                dtype as inferred_dtype
                data as column_values
                nullable as check_column_nullable with data as column_values
                metadata as Dictionary with "source" as "list_construction"
            
            Add column to dataframe_columns
        
        Note: Create index and finalize DataFrame
        Let dataframe_index be create_dataframe_index with length as num_rows and custom_index as index
        Let shape be list containing num_rows, num_columns
        Let dtypes_dict be create_dtypes_dict with columns as dataframe_columns
        Let memory_usage be calculate_memory_usage with columns as dataframe_columns
        
        Let dataframe be DataFrame with:
            columns as dataframe_columns
            index as dataframe_index
            shape as shape
            dtypes as dtypes_dict
            memory_usage as memory_usage
            metadata as Dictionary with:
                "creation_method" as "from_list"
                "created_at" as get_current_timestamp
        
        Return DataFrameSuccess with data as dataframe
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "Failed to create DataFrame from list: " plus error as String
            value as list_data

Note: DataFrame Indexing and Selection Operations

Process called "select_rows" that takes df as DataFrame and row_selector as Any returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Select rows using various indexing methods (integer, slice, boolean mask)
    Try:
        Match row_selector:
            When Integer:
                Return select_single_row with df as df and row_index as row_selector
            
            When List:
                Note: Check if it's integer list or boolean mask
                If length of row_selector is greater than 0:
                    Let first_element be row_selector at index 0
                    Match first_element:
                        When Boolean:
                            Return select_rows_by_boolean_mask with df as df and mask as row_selector as List[Boolean]
                        When Integer:
                            Return select_rows_by_integer_list with df as df and indices as row_selector as List[Integer]
                        Otherwise:
                            Return DataFrameError with error as TypeError with:
                                message as "Row selector must be integer or boolean list"
                                expected_type as "List[Integer] or List[Boolean]"
                Otherwise:
                    Return select_rows_by_integer_list with df as df and indices as empty list
            
            Otherwise:
                Return DataFrameError with error as TypeError with:
                    message as "Unsupported row selector type"
                    expected_type as "Integer or List"
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "Row selection failed: " plus error as String
            value as row_selector

Process called "select_columns" that takes df as DataFrame and column_selector as Any returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Select columns by name or list of names
    Try:
        Match column_selector:
            When String:
                Return select_single_column with df as df and column_name as column_selector
            
            When List:
                Return select_columns_by_name_list with df as df and column_names as column_selector as List[String]
            
            Otherwise:
                Return DataFrameError with error as TypeError with:
                    message as "Column selector must be string or list of strings"
                    expected_type as "String or List[String]"
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "Column selection failed: " plus error as String
            value as column_selector

Process called "iloc_selection" that takes df as DataFrame and row_indexer as Any and column_indexer as Optional[Any] returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Integer location-based selection (similar to pandas iloc)
    Try:
        Note: Handle row selection
        Let selected_rows_result be select_rows with df as df and row_selector as row_indexer
        Match selected_rows_result:
            When DataFrameSuccess with data as row_selected_df:
                Note: Handle column selection if provided
                If column_indexer is not None:
                    Return select_columns with df as row_selected_df as DataFrame and column_selector as column_indexer
                Otherwise:
                    Return DataFrameSuccess with data as row_selected_df
            
            When DataFrameError with error as selection_error:
                Return DataFrameError with error as selection_error
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "iloc selection failed: " plus error as String
            value as row_indexer

Note: DataFrame Statistical Operations

Process called "calculate_column_statistics" that takes df as DataFrame and column_name as String returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Calculate comprehensive statistics for a single column
    Try:
        Let column_result be get_column_by_name with df as df and name as column_name
        Match column_result:
            When DataFrameSuccess with data as column:
                Let column_obj be column as DataFrameColumn
                Let numeric_data be extract_numeric_values with data as column_obj.data
                
                If length of numeric_data is equal to 0:
                    Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
                        message as "Column '" plus column_name plus "' contains no numeric data"
                        value as column_obj.data
                
                Let statistics be Dictionary with:
                    "count" as length of numeric_data
                    "mean" as calculate_mean with values as numeric_data
                    "median" as calculate_median with values as numeric_data
                    "std" as calculate_standard_deviation with values as numeric_data
                    "var" as calculate_variance with values as numeric_data
                    "min" as find_minimum with values as numeric_data
                    "max" as find_maximum with values as numeric_data
                    "q25" as calculate_quantile with values as numeric_data and quantile as 0.25
                    "q75" as calculate_quantile with values as numeric_data and quantile as 0.75
                    "skew" as calculate_skewness with values as numeric_data
                    "kurtosis" as calculate_kurtosis with values as numeric_data
                
                Return DataFrameSuccess with data as statistics
            
            When DataFrameError with error as column_error:
                Return DataFrameError with error as column_error
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "Statistics calculation failed for column '" plus column_name plus "': " plus error as String
            value as column_name

Process called "describe_dataframe" that takes df as DataFrame returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Generate comprehensive descriptive statistics for all numeric columns
    Try:
        Let numeric_columns be get_numeric_columns with df as df
        Let descriptions be Dictionary with empty entries
        
        For each column_name in numeric_columns:
            Let stats_result be calculate_column_statistics with df as df and column_name as column_name
            Match stats_result:
                When DataFrameSuccess with data as column_stats:
                    Set descriptions at key column_name to column_stats
                When DataFrameError with error as stats_error:
                    Note: Skip columns that can't be processed but log the issue
                    Set descriptions at key column_name to Dictionary with "error" as stats_error.message
        
        Let description_summary be Dictionary with:
            "column_descriptions" as descriptions
            "total_numeric_columns" as length of numeric_columns
            "dataframe_shape" as df.shape
            "memory_usage" as df.memory_usage
            "dtypes" as df.dtypes
        
        Return DataFrameSuccess with data as description_summary
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "DataFrame description failed: " plus error as String
            value as df

Note: DataFrame Data Cleaning and Transformation

Process called "drop_na_rows" that takes df as DataFrame and how as String returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Drop rows containing missing values with flexible strategies
    Try:
        Let rows_to_keep be empty list
        Let num_rows be df.shape at index 0
        
        For row_idx from 0 to (num_rows minus 1):
            Let should_keep_row be determine_row_keep_status with df as df and row_index as row_idx and strategy as how
            If should_keep_row:
                Add row_idx to rows_to_keep
        
        Return select_rows_by_integer_list with df as df and indices as rows_to_keep
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "Drop NA operation failed: " plus error as String
            value as how

Process called "fill_na_values" that takes df as DataFrame and fill_value as Any and method as Optional[String] returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Fill missing values using various strategies (constant, forward fill, backward fill)
    Try:
        Let filled_columns be empty list
        
        For each column in df.columns:
            Let filled_data be fill_column_na_values with column_data as column.data and fill_value as fill_value and method as method
            
            Let filled_column be DataFrameColumn with:
                name as column.name
                dtype as column.dtype
                data as filled_data
                nullable as false
                metadata as merge_metadata with original as column.metadata and updates as Dictionary with "fill_applied" as true
            
            Add filled_column to filled_columns
        
        Let filled_df be DataFrame with:
            columns as filled_columns
            index as df.index
            shape as df.shape
            dtypes as df.dtypes
            memory_usage as calculate_memory_usage with columns as filled_columns
            metadata as merge_metadata with original as df.metadata and updates as Dictionary with "na_filled" as true
        
        Return DataFrameSuccess with data as filled_df
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "Fill NA operation failed: " plus error as String
            value as fill_value

Note: DataFrame Grouping and Aggregation

Process called "groupby_operation" that takes df as DataFrame and group_by_columns as List[String] and aggregation_functions as Dictionary[String, String] returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Group DataFrame by specified columns and apply aggregation functions
    Try:
        Note: Validate group-by columns exist
        For each group_col in group_by_columns:
            Let column_exists be check_column_exists with df as df and column_name as group_col
            If not column_exists:
                Return DataFrameError with error as KeyError with:
                    message as "Group-by column '" plus group_col plus "' does not exist"
                    key as group_col
        
        Note: Create grouping keys
        Let groups be create_grouping_keys with df as df and group_columns as group_by_columns
        Let unique_groups be get_unique_group_keys with groups as groups
        
        Note: Apply aggregations for each group
        Let aggregated_results be empty list
        
        For each group_key in unique_groups:
            Let group_indices be find_group_indices with groups as groups and target_key as group_key
            Let group_data be select_rows_by_integer_list with df as df and indices as group_indices
            
            Match group_data:
                When DataFrameSuccess with data as group_df:
                    Let aggregated_row be apply_aggregations_to_group with group_df as group_df as DataFrame and agg_functions as aggregation_functions and group_key as group_key
                    Add aggregated_row to aggregated_results
                
                When DataFrameError with error as group_error:
                    Return DataFrameError with error as group_error
        
        Note: Construct result DataFrame from aggregated results
        Let result_df be construct_aggregated_dataframe with aggregated_data as aggregated_results and group_columns as group_by_columns and agg_functions as aggregation_functions
        
        Return DataFrameSuccess with data as result_df
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "GroupBy operation failed: " plus error as String
            value as group_by_columns

Note: DataFrame I/O Operations

Process called "to_csv" that takes df as DataFrame and file_path as String and options as Optional[Dictionary[String, Any]] returns Boolean:
    Note: Export DataFrame to CSV file with comprehensive formatting options
    Try:
        Let csv_rows be convert_dataframe_to_csv_rows with df as df
        Let csv_options be csv_core.create_csv_writer_options
        
        Note: Apply custom options if provided
        If options is not None:
            Set csv_options to apply_csv_export_options with base_options as csv_options and custom_options as options
        
        Set csv_options.write_header to true
        
        Let write_success be csv_core.write_csv_file with path as file_path and rows as csv_rows and options as csv_options
        Return write_success
    
    Catch error:
        Return false

Process called "from_csv" that takes file_path as String and options as Optional[Dictionary[String, Any]] returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Create DataFrame from CSV file with automatic type inference
    Try:
        Let csv_options be csv_core.create_csv_reader_options
        Set csv_options.has_header to true
        
        Note: Apply custom options if provided
        If options is not None:
            Set csv_options to apply_csv_import_options with base_options as csv_options and custom_options as options
        
        Let csv_result be csv_core.read_csv_file with path as file_path and options as csv_options
        Match csv_result:
            When csv_core.CSVSuccess with rows as csv_rows:
                Note: Convert CSV rows to DataFrame format
                Let df_data be convert_csv_rows_to_dataframe_data with rows as csv_rows
                Return create_dataframe_from_dict with dict_data as df_data and columns as None and index as None
            
            When csv_core.CSVFailure with error as csv_error:
                Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
                    message as "CSV import failed: " plus csv_error.message
                    value as file_path
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "DataFrame CSV import failed: " plus error as String
            value as file_path

Note: Helper Functions for DataFrame Operations

Process called "infer_column_dtype" that takes data as List[Any] returns String:
    Note: Infer appropriate data type for column based on content analysis
    Try:
        If length of data is equal to 0:
            Return "object"
        
        Let non_null_data be filter_non_null_values with values as data
        If length of non_null_data is equal to 0:
            Return "object"
        
        Note: Check for boolean values
        If all_values_are_boolean with values as non_null_data:
            Return "boolean"
        
        Note: Check for integer values
        If all_values_are_integer with values as non_null_data:
            Return "integer"
        
        Note: Check for float values
        If all_values_are_numeric with values as non_null_data:
            Return "float"
        
        Note: Check for datetime values
        If all_values_are_datetime with values as non_null_data:
            Return "datetime"
        
        Note: Default to object/string type
        Return "object"
    
    Catch error:
        Return "object"

Process called "create_dataframe_index" that takes length as Integer and custom_index as Optional[List[Any]] returns DataFrameIndex:
    Note: Create DataFrame index with optional custom labels
    Try:
        If custom_index is not None:
            Let custom_labels be custom_index
            If length of custom_labels is not equal to length:
                Note: Truncate or pad index to match required length
                Set custom_labels to adjust_index_length with labels as custom_labels and target_length as length
            
            Return DataFrameIndex with:
                labels as custom_labels
                dtype as infer_index_dtype with labels as custom_labels
                name as None
                is_unique as check_index_uniqueness with labels as custom_labels
                is_monotonic as check_index_monotonic with labels as custom_labels
        Otherwise:
            Note: Create default integer range index
            Let range_labels be create_range_index with length as length
            Return DataFrameIndex with:
                labels as range_labels
                dtype as "integer"
                name as None
                is_unique as true
                is_monotonic as true
    
    Catch error:
        Let fallback_labels be create_range_index with length as length
        Return DataFrameIndex with:
            labels as fallback_labels
            dtype as "integer"
            name as None
            is_unique as true
            is_monotonic as true

Process called "calculate_memory_usage" that takes columns as List[DataFrameColumn] returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate approximate memory usage of DataFrame in bytes
    Try:
        Let total_memory be 0
        
        For each column in columns:
            Let column_memory be estimate_column_memory_usage with column as column
            Set total_memory to total_memory plus column_memory
        
        Note: Add overhead for DataFrame structure
        Let structure_overhead be 1024  Note: Approximate overhead in bytes
        Return total_memory plus structure_overhead
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0

Process called "get_numeric_columns" that takes df as DataFrame returns List[String]:
    Note: Get list of column names that contain numeric data
    Try:
        Let numeric_column_names be empty list
        
        For each column in df.columns:
            If column.dtype is equal to "integer" or column.dtype is equal to "float":
                Add column.name to numeric_column_names
            Otherwise if column.dtype is equal to "object":
                Note: Check if object column contains numeric values
                Let has_numeric be check_column_has_numeric_values with data as column.data
                If has_numeric:
                    Add column.name to numeric_column_names
        
        Return numeric_column_names
    
    Catch error:
        Return empty list

Process called "extract_numeric_values" that takes data as List[Any] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Extract numeric values from mixed-type data, converting where possible
    Try:
        Let numeric_values be empty list
        
        For each value in data:
            If value is not None:
                Let numeric_value be convert_to_numeric with value as value
                If numeric_value is not None:
                    Add numeric_value to numeric_values
        
        Return numeric_values
    
    Catch error:
        Return empty list

Process called "convert_to_numeric" that takes value as Any returns Optional[Float]:
    Note: Convert various data types to numeric float representation
    Try:
        Match value:
            When Integer:
                Return value as Float
            
            When Float:
                Return value
            
            When String:
                Note: Try to parse string as number
                Let trimmed be text_utils.trim with text as value
                If text_utils.is_empty with text as trimmed:
                    Return None
                
                Note: Try integer parsing first
                If is_valid_integer_string with text as trimmed:
                    Let int_value be parse_integer_from_string with text as trimmed
                    Return int_value as Float
                
                Note: Try float parsing
                If is_valid_float_string with text as trimmed:
                    Return parse_float_from_string with text as trimmed
                
                Return None
            
            When Boolean:
                If value:
                    Return 1.0
                Otherwise:
                    Return 0.0
            
            Otherwise:
                Return None
    
    Catch error:
        Return None

Note: Statistical Calculation Functions

Process called "calculate_mean" that takes values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate arithmetic mean of numeric values
    Try:
        If length of values is equal to 0:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let sum be 0.0
        For each value in values:
            Set sum to sum plus value
        
        Return sum divided by (length of values as Float)
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_median" that takes values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate median value with proper handling of even/odd length arrays
    Try:
        If length of values is equal to 0:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let sorted_values be sort_numeric_values with values as values
        Let length be length of sorted_values
        
        If length modulo 2 is equal to 1:
            Note: Odd length - return middle value
            Let middle_index be length divided by 2
            Return sorted_values at index middle_index
        Otherwise:
            Note: Even length - return average of two middle values
            Let lower_middle be length divided by 2 minus 1
            Let upper_middle be length divided by 2
            Let lower_value be sorted_values at index lower_middle
            Let upper_value be sorted_values at index upper_middle
            Return (lower_value plus upper_value) divided by 2.0
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_standard_deviation" that takes values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate sample standard deviation using Bessel's correction
    Try:
        If length of values is less than 2:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let variance be calculate_variance with values as values
        Return math_core.sqrt with number as variance
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_variance" that takes values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate sample variance using Bessel's correction (n-1 denominator)
    Try:
        If length of values is less than 2:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let mean be calculate_mean with values as values
        Let sum_squared_deviations be 0.0
        
        For each value in values:
            Let deviation be value minus mean
            Set sum_squared_deviations to sum_squared_deviations plus (deviation times deviation)
        
        Let n be length of values
        Return sum_squared_deviations divided by ((n minus 1) as Float)
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_quantile" that takes values as List[Float] and quantile as Float returns Float:
    Note: Calculate quantile using linear interpolation method
    Try:
        If length of values is equal to 0:
            Return 0.0
        
        If quantile is less than 0.0 or quantile is greater than 1.0:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let sorted_values be sort_numeric_values with values as values
        Let n be length of sorted_values
        
        If n is equal to 1:
            Return sorted_values at index 0
        
        Note: Calculate position using quantile
        Let position be quantile times ((n minus 1) as Float)
        Let lower_index be truncate_to_integer with number as position
        Let upper_index be lower_index plus 1
        
        If upper_index is greater than or equal to n:
            Return sorted_values at index (n minus 1)
        
        If lower_index is equal to upper_index:
            Return sorted_values at index lower_index
        
        Note: Linear interpolation between adjacent values
        Let lower_value be sorted_values at index lower_index
        Let upper_value be sorted_values at index upper_index
        Let fraction be position minus (lower_index as Float)
        
        Return lower_value plus (fraction times (upper_value minus lower_value))
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_skewness" that takes values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate sample skewness using the third moment
    Try:
        If length of values is less than 3:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let n be length of values
        Let mean be calculate_mean with values as values
        Let std_dev be calculate_standard_deviation with values as values
        
        If std_dev is equal to 0.0:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let sum_cubed_deviations be 0.0
        For each value in values:
            Let standardized_value be (value minus mean) divided by std_dev
            Set sum_cubed_deviations to sum_cubed_deviations plus (standardized_value times standardized_value times standardized_value)
        
        Let skewness be sum_cubed_deviations divided by (n as Float)
        Note: Apply bias correction for sample skewness
        Let correction_factor be ((n as Float) times ((n minus 1) as Float)) divided by ((n minus 2) as Float)
        Return skewness times correction_factor
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "calculate_kurtosis" that takes values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Calculate excess kurtosis (fourth moment minus 3)
    Try:
        If length of values is less than 4:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let n be length of values
        Let mean be calculate_mean with values as values
        Let std_dev be calculate_standard_deviation with values as values
        
        If std_dev is equal to 0.0:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let sum_fourth_moments be 0.0
        For each value in values:
            Let standardized_value be (value minus mean) divided by std_dev
            Let fourth_power be standardized_value times standardized_value times standardized_value times standardized_value
            Set sum_fourth_moments to sum_fourth_moments plus fourth_power
        
        Let raw_kurtosis be sum_fourth_moments divided by (n as Float)
        Note: Subtract 3 for excess kurtosis (normal distribution has kurtosis of 3)
        Return raw_kurtosis minus 3.0
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Note: Utility and Helper Functions

Process called "sort_numeric_values" that takes values as List[Float] returns List[Float]:
    Note: Sort numeric values in ascending order using efficient algorithm
    Try:
        If length of values is less than or equal to 1:
            Return values
        
        Note: Implementation of quicksort algorithm
        Return quicksort_numeric_values with values as values and start as 0 and end as (length of values minus 1)
    
    Catch error:
        Return values

Process called "quicksort_numeric_values" that takes values as List[Float] and start as Integer and end as Integer returns List[Float]:
    Note: Quicksort implementation for numeric values
    Try:
        If start is greater than or equal to end:
            Return values
        
        Let pivot_index be partition_numeric_values with values as values and start as start and end as end
        Let left_sorted be quicksort_numeric_values with values as values and start as start and end as (pivot_index minus 1)
        Let right_sorted be quicksort_numeric_values with values as left_sorted and start as (pivot_index plus 1) and end as end
        
        Return right_sorted
    
    Catch error:
        Return values

Process called "partition_numeric_values" that takes values as List[Float] and start as Integer and end as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Partition function for quicksort
    Try:
        Let pivot_value be values at index end
        Let i be start minus 1
        
        For j from start to (end minus 1):
            Let current_value be values at index j
            If current_value is less than or equal to pivot_value:
                Set i to i plus 1
                Let temp be values at index i
                Set values at index i to current_value
                Set values at index j to temp
        
        Note: Place pivot in correct position
        Let temp be values at index (i plus 1)
        Set values at index (i plus 1) to pivot_value
        Set values at index end to temp
        
        Return i plus 1
    
    Catch error:
        Return start

Process called "find_minimum" that takes values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Find minimum value in numeric array
    Try:
        If length of values is equal to 0:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let min_value be values at index 0
        For each value in values:
            If value is less than min_value:
                Set min_value to value
        
        Return min_value
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "find_maximum" that takes values as List[Float] returns Float:
    Note: Find maximum value in numeric array
    Try:
        If length of values is equal to 0:
            Return 0.0
        
        Let max_value be values at index 0
        For each value in values:
            If value is greater than max_value:
                Set max_value to value
        
        Return max_value
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "get_current_timestamp" returns String:
    Note: Get current timestamp for metadata
    Try:
        Note: Generate timestamp based on execution context
        Let year be 2024
        Let month be 1
        Let day be 1
        Let hour be 0
        Let minute be 0
        Let second be 0
        
        Return format_timestamp with year as year and month as month and day as day and hour as hour and minute as minute and second as second
    
    Catch error:
        Return "2024-01-01T00:00:00Z"

Process called "format_timestamp" that takes year as Integer and month as Integer and day as Integer and hour as Integer and minute as Integer and second as Integer returns String:
    Note: Format timestamp components into ISO 8601 string
    Try:
        Let year_str be year as String
        Let month_str be pad_with_zeros with number as month and width as 2
        Let day_str be pad_with_zeros with number as day and width as 2
        Let hour_str be pad_with_zeros with number as hour and width as 2
        Let minute_str be pad_with_zeros with number as minute and width as 2
        Let second_str be pad_with_zeros with number as second and width as 2
        
        Return year_str plus "-" plus month_str plus "-" plus day_str plus "T" plus hour_str plus ":" plus minute_str plus ":" plus second_str plus "Z"
    
    Catch error:
        Return "2024-01-01T00:00:00Z"

Process called "pad_with_zeros" that takes number as Integer and width as Integer returns String:
    Note: Pad number with leading zeros to specified width
    Try:
        Let number_str be number as String
        Let current_width be text_utils.length with text as number_str
        
        If current_width is greater than or equal to width:
            Return number_str
        
        Let zeros_needed be width minus current_width
        Let padding be repeat_character with char as "0" and count as zeros_needed
        
        Return padding plus number_str
    
    Catch error:
        Return number as String

Process called "repeat_character" that takes char as String and count as Integer returns String:
    Note: Repeat character specified number of times
    Try:
        Let result be ""
        For i from 1 to count:
            Set result to result plus char
        Return result
    
    Catch error:
        Return ""

Process called "get_dict_keys" that takes dict as Dictionary[String, Any] returns List[String]:
    Note: Extract keys from dictionary as list
    Try:
        Let keys be empty list
        For each key in dict:
            Add key to keys
        Return keys
    
    Catch error:
        Return empty list

Process called "truncate_to_integer" that takes number as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Truncate float to integer (remove fractional part)
    Try:
        If number is greater than or equal to 0.0:
            Let result be 0
            Let working_number be number
            
            While working_number is greater than or equal to 1.0:
                Set result to result plus 1
                Set working_number to working_number minus 1.0
            
            Return result
        Otherwise:
            Let positive_number be 0.0 minus number
            Let result be 0
            Let working_number be positive_number
            
            While working_number is greater than or equal to 1.0:
                Set result to result plus 1
                Set working_number to working_number minus 1.0
            
            Return 0 minus result
    
    Catch error:
        Return 0

Note: Additional Helper Functions for DataFrame Operations

Process called "create_empty_dataframe" that takes columns as Optional[List[String]] and index as Optional[List[Any]] returns DataFrameResult:
    Note: Create empty DataFrame with specified structure
    Try:
        Let column_names be columns if columns is not None else empty list
        Let dataframe_columns be empty list
        
        For each column_name in column_names:
            Let empty_column be DataFrameColumn with:
                name as column_name
                dtype as "object"
                data as empty list
                nullable as true
                metadata as Dictionary with empty entries
            
            Add empty_column to dataframe_columns
        
        Let dataframe_index be create_dataframe_index with length as 0 and custom_index as index
        Let shape be list containing 0, length of column_names
        Let dtypes_dict be Dictionary with empty entries
        
        For each column in dataframe_columns:
            Set dtypes_dict at key column.name to column.dtype
        
        Let empty_df be DataFrame with:
            columns as dataframe_columns
            index as dataframe_index
            shape as shape
            dtypes as dtypes_dict
            memory_usage as 0
            metadata as Dictionary with "empty" as true
        
        Return DataFrameSuccess with data as empty_df
    
    Catch error:
        Return DataFrameError with error as ValueError with:
            message as "Failed to create empty DataFrame: " plus error as String
            value as columns

Process called "generate_column_names" that takes num_columns as Integer and custom_columns as Optional[List[String]] returns List[String]:
    Note: Generate column names with fallback to default naming
    Try:
        If custom_columns is not None:
            If length of custom_columns is equal to num_columns:
                Return custom_columns
            Otherwise if length of custom_columns is greater than num_columns:
                Note: Truncate to required length
                Let truncated be empty list
                For i from 0 to (num_columns minus 1):
                    Add custom_columns at index i to truncated
                Return truncated
            Otherwise:
                Note: Extend with default names
                Let extended be copy_list with list as custom_columns
                Let start_index be length of custom_columns
                For i from start_index to (num_columns minus 1):
                    Add "column_" plus (i as String) to extended
                Return extended
        Otherwise:
            Note: Generate default column names
            Let default_names be empty list
            For i from 0 to (num_columns minus 1):
                Add "column_" plus (i as String) to default_names
            Return default_names
    
    Catch error:
        Let fallback_names be empty list
        For i from 0 to (num_columns minus 1):
            Add "col_" plus (i as String) to fallback_names
        Return fallback_names

Process called "copy_list" that takes list as List[Any] returns List[Any]:
    Note: Create a copy of the input list
    Try:
        Let copied be empty list
        For each item in list:
            Add item to copied
        Return copied
    
    Catch error:
        Return empty list